1)  Analysis of the Main Target Image

•  Block Count & Layers  
  – There are 6 total blocks in the structure:  
     → Four small colored cubes (green, orange, blue, red).  
     → Two long yellow rectangular bars (one on top, one on the bottom).  
  – They form three “layers” if you count from bottom to top:  
     1. A bottom horizontal yellow bar,  
     2. Two vertical stacks of colored cubes (orange under green on the left; red under blue on the right),  
     3. A top horizontal yellow bar.

•  Spatial Relationships  
  – Left column: orange cube sits directly on the bottom yellow bar, with the green cube stacked on top of the orange.  
  – Right column: red cube sits on the bottom yellow bar, with the blue cube stacked on top of the red.  
  – A long yellow bar spans across both columns at the bottom, and an identical long bar spans the top.

2)  Selecting the Required Blocks from the Dictionary

•  Needed Blocks & Indices  
  – Green cube: index 2  
  – Orange cube: index 3  
  – Blue cube: index 1  
  – Red cube: index 4  
  – Long yellow horizontal bars (top and bottom): index 6 (used twice)

•  Exact Matching  
  – All four colored cubes must come from their matching “cube” entries (1 = blue, 2 = green, 3 = orange, 4 = red).  
  – The horizontal yellow bars must come from index 6, which appears already oriented horizontally.  
  – No rotation is needed or allowed; use each block exactly as shown.

3)  Step-by-Step Assembly Instructions

{
  Step1: Move block with index 6   // Place the bottom yellow bar
  Step2: Move block with index 3   // Place the orange cube on left
  Step3: Move block with index 2   // Stack the green cube on top of the orange
  Step4: Move block with index 4   // Place the red cube on right
  Step5: Move block with index 1   // Stack the blue cube on top of the red
  Step6: Move block with index 6   // Place the top yellow bar
}
